1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:26,780
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassam Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassam Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassam

2
00:00:27,300 --> 00:00:32,887
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:32,908 --> 00:00:35,993
So, I'm going to start on the ten perfections.

4
00:00:36,372 --> 00:00:37,554
I'll just run through them quickly.

5
00:00:37,674 --> 00:00:46,045
Generosity, morality, renunciation, wisdom, energy, patience, truthfulness, resolution, loving-kindness and equanimity.

6
00:00:46,406 --> 00:00:49,189
We won't do them all tonight.

7
00:00:49,210 --> 00:00:52,734
We'll just do the dana, which is generosity.

8
00:00:53,085 --> 00:01:02,718
Dāna is the sort of core virtue for the Buddha because whenever he's teaching laypeople he always starts with Dāna, generosity.

9
00:01:03,618 --> 00:01:09,426
And the reason is that you can be completely immoral and yet be generous.

10
00:01:09,486 --> 00:01:12,688
So a thief can be very generous even if it's with your money.

11
00:01:15,132 --> 00:01:21,540
So it's like a quality that can exist prior to a good morality.

12
00:01:22,043 --> 00:01:34,603
And then he always then talks about morality, then he goes on to rebirth, and then finally when he feels that the audience is open enough, he hits them with the Four Noble Truths.

13
00:01:35,185 --> 00:01:38,831
So he has his way of gradual teaching.

14
00:01:42,177 --> 00:01:44,861
By the way, when you hear Dāna within Buddhist company,

15
00:01:45,230 --> 00:01:53,283
they're normally referring to giving food to monks, because that's, you know, when they say they're giving dana, that's what they're normally referring to.

16
00:01:55,165 --> 00:02:02,096
And the whole point about generosity, of course, that undermines selfishness, you know, this, you know, what's in it for me, you know.

17
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:04,521
And

18
00:02:05,885 --> 00:02:10,151
I mean, our society is particularly selfish, I think, compared to others.

19
00:02:13,317 --> 00:02:18,044
And that's the enemy of generosity, selfishness.

20
00:02:18,944 --> 00:02:27,217
The more subtle enemy, of course, is the feeling of doing it for feeling good, and we'll come to that in a minute.

21
00:02:27,198 --> 00:02:36,310
Now, the scriptures talk about three conditions for a wholesome giving.

22
00:02:38,272 --> 00:02:47,965
If you're offering wealth, if you're offering money as a donation, it has to be earned virtuously.

23
00:02:48,887 --> 00:02:51,409
It's interesting, isn't it?

24
00:02:51,449 --> 00:02:53,812
If you just thieved it from the bank, if not...

25
00:02:54,855 --> 00:02:58,861
It's like if people win on the lottery, you see.

26
00:02:59,522 --> 00:03:12,341
Now, you know, it's no big evil thing to win some money in the lottery, but it's still based on, you know, taking money from other people.

27
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:19,471
Even though the other people have gladly put their money in, it's still a sort of slightly off way of earning money.

28
00:03:19,591 --> 00:03:22,194
Gambling is a form of gambling.

29
00:03:23,235 --> 00:03:23,817
And so...

30
00:03:24,201 --> 00:03:31,890
Even if you were to give that money, there would be just that little bit of unwholesomeness about it.

31
00:03:33,973 --> 00:03:38,638
In fact, I know of one person who won a lot of money.

32
00:03:38,998 --> 00:03:41,382
He was a Muslim and he offered it to his mosque.

33
00:03:41,401 --> 00:03:42,182
They wouldn't receive it.

34
00:03:42,223 --> 00:03:42,943
They wouldn't take it.

35
00:03:46,647 --> 00:03:52,234
And the gift itself, like the amount you give, has to be appropriate, has to be wise.

36
00:03:52,687 --> 00:04:01,576
Somebody was telling me just now that somebody's bought their daughter, I think she's 12 years old, a 500-pound watch.

37
00:04:03,278 --> 00:04:05,861
It's pretty much, isn't it?

38
00:04:06,682 --> 00:04:09,265
What does it do to a kid of that age?

39
00:04:09,705 --> 00:04:15,453
So it's like you've got to be sort of wise about the amount you give.

40
00:04:15,953 --> 00:04:18,596
And the receiver themselves has to be worthy of your gift.

41
00:04:19,156 --> 00:04:20,077
They have to be worthy of it.

42
00:04:20,834 --> 00:04:23,560
So, I mean, it's no good giving a month tickets to Las Vegas.

43
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:27,648
I mean, it's not, it wouldn't be right, you know.

44
00:04:27,668 --> 00:04:34,862
And, like, but, you know, when people ask you for money on the streets, so you have to be careful, you know.

45
00:04:34,882 --> 00:04:40,615
I mean, I always, you know, it's like, you know that they're either going to use it for drugs or for,

46
00:04:41,201 --> 00:05:08,982
offer you know so it's it's one of those little dodgy things i mean if you say well look i'll buy you a hamburger and they say well i don't want to eat and you know they just want your money for a bit more drink in fact there was once in london and this this young guy came up to me says uh can you give me some can you help me he says i said why do you want it he said well i want to buy some hash i don't want to do that he says oh come on he said i'm being truthful i thought well i

47
00:05:11,324 --> 00:05:37,550
he thought because he was being truthful therefore he was worthy of a gift you see it's funny and it's the same when you offer to do something for somebody so you're offering time in that case in which case you know you have to be careful of your motives and often we think we're doing something out of you know the pure heart but there's a subliminal unconscious

48
00:05:38,391 --> 00:05:41,596
unconscious little conditions that we put on things, you know.

49
00:05:42,177 --> 00:05:46,502
You have to be quite open to any negative feelings.

50
00:05:46,541 --> 00:06:00,298
Now, remember that if you're offering to do something for somebody and you're aware of these little things that, you know, well, they might give me some money when I'm finished, something like that.

51
00:06:00,959 --> 00:06:05,125
Remember that to be aware of it is not to be dominated by it.

52
00:06:05,105 --> 00:06:17,403
So you can still be aware of that unwholesome thought and then determine that you're going to do it for wholesome reasons.

53
00:06:19,247 --> 00:06:22,471
Because there's an intention there, it's not activated, you see.

54
00:06:24,612 --> 00:06:32,000
And when it's subliminal, when it's unconscious, it can have an effect on what we're doing.

55
00:06:32,161 --> 00:06:35,786
And then you know that afterwards when they don't give you anything and you're upset.

56
00:06:36,947 --> 00:06:40,572
So then you know that there's been some sort of subliminal reason for doing something.

57
00:06:41,934 --> 00:06:49,302
So our awareness, our mindfulness puts us in contact with these little subterranean desires.

58
00:06:52,269 --> 00:06:54,055
And of course what you're doing is worthy.

59
00:06:54,656 --> 00:06:59,730
It's no good saying to the judge, I was only helping him rob the bank.

60
00:06:59,750 --> 00:07:00,492
I didn't want any money.

61
00:07:01,276 --> 00:07:07,392
The act itself has to be virtuous, has to be wholesome.

62
00:07:08,098 --> 00:07:10,843
And again, the person has to be worthy of the gift.

63
00:07:10,862 --> 00:07:13,307
You have to feel they're worthy of it.

64
00:07:13,646 --> 00:07:23,021
Often when you have a next-door neighbor who's elderly, and they want a bit of help, so obviously that's...

65
00:07:23,040 --> 00:07:25,144
But I remember I used to visit a friend of mine.

66
00:07:25,163 --> 00:07:27,266
Every time you turned up, they'd say, Oh, I'm glad you've come.

67
00:07:27,608 --> 00:07:28,509
Can you help me do this?

68
00:07:28,990 --> 00:07:32,454
And after a while you think, Well, I've got to stop going, frankly.

69
00:07:33,437 --> 00:07:35,119
I've got to be a bit abused now.

70
00:07:37,951 --> 00:08:06,000
so those qualities about the virtue of your giving the purpose of your giving what it is you're actually giving and the virtue of the person who is receiving your gift and that makes the perfect gift and when you make an offering

71
00:08:06,502 --> 00:08:12,471
often we do it quite impulsively and then often we regret what we've given or what we've done.

72
00:08:13,372 --> 00:08:34,822
And if we can get into the habit of just stopping for a moment and just saying, well, I'll think about it or I'll just consider that for a minute and just get the right attitude going, when you actually give something or decide to do something for somebody, just make sure that you've actually phrased it within yourself

73
00:08:35,477 --> 00:08:37,379
to make that offering pure.

74
00:08:38,240 --> 00:08:43,284
You say something like, well, I'm giving this without any hope of return, or I'm doing this, you know.

75
00:08:43,304 --> 00:08:49,250
That doesn't stop you doing things, offering things which aren't, shall we say, pure generosity.

76
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:54,394
I mean, there are, you know, like at Christmas you give presents and you get one back.

77
00:08:54,413 --> 00:08:54,934
That's all right.

78
00:08:54,955 --> 00:08:56,576
It's a social interaction.

79
00:08:58,357 --> 00:08:59,578
It's not evil to do that.

80
00:08:59,859 --> 00:09:03,642
It's just that there's always, it's not coming from the pure heart.

81
00:09:04,423 --> 00:09:04,523
Okay?

82
00:09:08,991 --> 00:09:25,736
And remember that if you do give something, or you do something for somebody, and then you get this little voice come back, you know, like saying, truly you are a most generous person, you know, you're quite extraordinary, your virtue is above everybody else.

83
00:09:25,756 --> 00:09:36,754
So when you hear that little voice, you see, you point to it and say, ah, I see you, Mara, the evil one, but it didn't actually affect my action, you see, so therefore it didn't have the effect it would normally have of making

84
00:09:37,004 --> 00:09:38,986
of making what we do a little selfish.

85
00:09:39,908 --> 00:09:49,423
So it's seeing our unwholesome intentions which disempowers them.

86
00:09:50,304 --> 00:09:57,797
It's when we don't see them that they creep up behind us and then we realize afterwards that there have been unwholesome intentions.

87
00:10:01,202 --> 00:10:09,273
And I suppose it's a paradox when you think that the more you give with that way, the more joyful you feel.

88
00:10:09,354 --> 00:10:12,798
But it's because we can rejoice in another person's joy.

89
00:10:13,578 --> 00:10:16,543
That's why we feel joyful when we help somebody.

90
00:10:17,783 --> 00:10:20,607
And then, of course, the mistake arises.

91
00:10:20,648 --> 00:10:22,110
You start doing it in order to feel good.

92
00:10:22,610 --> 00:10:22,750
See?

93
00:10:23,010 --> 00:10:24,013
And the whole thing.

94
00:10:24,033 --> 00:10:25,413
So let's be careful.

95
00:10:27,177 --> 00:10:28,057
Mara's tricky.

96
00:10:28,918 --> 00:10:28,999
Huh?

97
00:10:32,201 --> 00:10:34,451
And the last thing is about spontaneity.

98
00:10:35,174 --> 00:10:37,303
Spontaneity doesn't arrive spontaneously.

99
00:10:37,947 --> 00:10:39,493
You've got to work at it.

100
00:10:40,056 --> 00:10:41,722
So if you think of sports people

101
00:10:41,904 --> 00:10:50,479
I mean, like a tennis player, they're just acting, you can't even call it a reaction really.

102
00:10:50,820 --> 00:10:54,306
I mean, they're totally in the game, with the game, acting spontaneously.

103
00:10:54,846 --> 00:10:57,230
But they've done hours of practice, you see.

104
00:10:57,731 --> 00:11:05,684
So at first it might seem that this is a force, contrived, you see.

105
00:11:06,086 --> 00:11:09,212
And you're sort of playing this game of saying, well, why am I doing that?

106
00:11:09,232 --> 00:11:10,956
Okay, here I give with the fullness of my heart.

107
00:11:11,378 --> 00:11:16,288
But it's through the practice of that, that eventually you find yourself doing things spontaneously.

108
00:11:18,131 --> 00:11:24,585
Which is slightly different from doing something impulsively from old conditionings, which you normally tend to regret.

109
00:11:25,460 --> 00:11:28,765
So if you're like me, you tend to say yes too quickly.

110
00:11:29,687 --> 00:11:33,354
You do the yes, and then you think, I don't want to do that.

111
00:11:33,374 --> 00:11:34,174
What do I say that for?

112
00:11:35,417 --> 00:11:37,981
So it's getting out of that, getting out of that habit.

113
00:11:38,442 --> 00:11:42,690
And it's not insulting to somebody to say, well, hold on, I'll have to think about that.

114
00:11:43,110 --> 00:11:49,442
It just gives you a bit of a space to make the right intention, and then there's no regrets.

115
00:11:51,498 --> 00:11:57,745
So, just remember those three factors, just to end off with that.

116
00:11:58,927 --> 00:12:00,148
What is your intention?

117
00:12:01,350 --> 00:12:02,772
Is the gift worthy?

118
00:12:02,991 --> 00:12:04,333
Is it coming from a worthy place?

119
00:12:05,254 --> 00:12:10,120
And is the person you're helping, in some way or other, worthy of the gift?

120
00:12:11,101 --> 00:12:17,909
So, that's why they say the most perfect of all gifts is to give it to somebody who's fully enlightened.

121
00:12:18,413 --> 00:12:24,739
If you put an advert in the paper and say, you know, is anybody fully enlightened because I want to make this perfect gift?

122
00:12:24,759 --> 00:12:43,837
Because in doing it with a perfect heart and giving exactly what the person wants, and this person is, you know, very worthy of your gift, because they've perfected the path, and through that example they spread, you know, merit into the world.

123
00:12:43,857 --> 00:12:46,581
Merit is a funny way of translating paññā.

124
00:12:46,561 --> 00:12:49,504
I found a very good translation for it.

125
00:12:49,563 --> 00:12:50,384
It's goodness power.

126
00:12:51,746 --> 00:12:52,528
Goodness power.

127
00:12:52,548 --> 00:12:53,928
I thought it was a really good translation.

128
00:13:00,256 --> 00:13:02,698
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

129
00:13:03,299 --> 00:13:11,269
May you be fully liberated from all insidious intentions sooner rather than later.

130
00:13:13,054 --> 00:13:17,192
Adi Do, Adi Do, Adi Do.

